# Follow the Constitution

When product intent, architecture, repo layout, or conventions are unclear, read the constitution before guessing from code alone.

**Start here:** [constitution/index.md](../../constitution/index.md)

| Topic | File |
| --- | --- |
| Product intent | [constitution/_intent.md](../../constitution/_intent.md) |
| Tech stack | [constitution/_tech-stack.md](../../constitution/_tech-stack.md) |
| Monorepo layout | [constitution/_monorepo.md](../../constitution/_monorepo.md) |
| Agent workflow | [constitution/_agent-rules.md](../../constitution/_agent-rules.md) |

## Authority

1. **Constitution** — product intent and monorepo shape.
2. **Code** — source of truth for behavior; update constitution when decisions change.

## When to apply

- Starting ambiguous or cross-package work
- Choosing architecture, tooling, or new patterns
- Changing product behavior or repo layout
- Unsure whether a change fits desktop-first / web-builds-first flow

## Agent expectations

- Read the index and relevant `_*.md` topic before introducing new patterns.
- Match existing package conventions; minimize scope.
- Do not hand-edit generated assets under `packages/desktop/resources/` — run `copy-web-to-desktop` after web builds.
- Edit player-facing dialogue/labels under `packages/data/src/copy/` (see that folder’s README); keep effects/weights/ids in TypeScript.
- Update constitution docs when product or architecture decisions change.

## Quality gates

Before finishing substantive changes:

```bash
bun run lint:fix
bun run typecheck
```
